docs.abstract: Black artists objected after they discovered their work had been acquired by the museum through discounted sales meant to benefit charities.
docs.snippet: Black artists objected after they discovered their work had been acquired by the museum through discounted sales meant to benefit charities.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Whitney Museum of American Art on Tuesday canceled an upcoming exhibition after artists of color objected to the institution’s having obtained their work through discounted sales largely meant to benefit racial justice charities. They have accused the museum of trying to capitalize on their work without properly compensating them.

headline.main: Whitney Cancels Show That Included Works Bought at Fund-Raisers
headline.print_headline: Whitney Cancels Show Over Art Deals

byline.original: By Julia Jacobs and Zachary Small

docs.abstract: People in rural areas are killed in police shootings at about the same rate as in cities, but victims’ families and activists say they have struggled to get justice or even make themselves heard.
docs.snippet: People in rural areas are killed in police shootings at about the same rate as in cities, but victims’ families and activists say they have struggled to get justice or even make themselves heard.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEDALIA, Mo. — Seven weeks had passed, and still there were no answers. So once again, a small cluster of friends and family gathered in the leafy courthouse square and marched for Hannah Fizer, an unarmed woman shot and killed by a rural Missouri sheriff’s deputy during a traffic stop.

headline.main: A Family Cries ‘Justice for Hannah.’ Will Its Rural Town Listen?
headline.print_headline: In Rural Towns, Similar Chants To Find Justice

docs.abstract: The city briefly raised most of the bridges to the main shopping and business district. Mayor Lori Lightfoot condemned the crowd’s actions as “abject criminal behavior.”
docs.snippet: The city briefly raised most of the bridges to the main shopping and business district. Mayor Lori Lightfoot condemned the crowd’s actions as “abject criminal behavior.”
docs.lead_paragraph: CHICAGO — All summer, demonstrators have marched through Chicago to protest police misconduct. In many neighborhoods, gun violence has been unrelenting, soaring to levels not seen in decades. The coronavirus pandemic is resurging, now sickening hundreds of people each day.

headline.main: Chicago Police Arrest More Than 100 People After Looting Batters Downtown
headline.print_headline: Chicago Staggers Anew in a Torrent of Looting

byline.original: By Julie Bosman, Christine Hauser and Johnny Diaz

docs.abstract: The burst of creativity that has swept through town in recent weeks could provide a road map for other cities confronting historical racism.
docs.snippet: The burst of creativity that has swept through town in recent weeks could provide a road map for other cities confronting historical racism.
docs.lead_paragraph: Over the years, Bobby Fouther has watched the historic center of African-American life in Portland bloom, shrink and expand again. The 69-year-old artist was born into a creative family from the neighborhood of Albina, which he remembers filled with jazz music and beauty. “Black artists were thriving here in the 1950s,” he recalled. “My parents had turned our grandfather’s garage into a miniature theater, where my stepfather and his friends would perform late into the night.”

headline.main: Black Artists Find Ways to Make Their Voices Heard in Portland
headline.print_headline: Black Artists in Portland Make Themselves Heard

docs.abstract: The cancellation of a speech reflects an intense debate on the left: Is racism the primary problem in America today, or the outgrowth of a system that oppresses all poor people?
docs.snippet: The cancellation of a speech reflects an intense debate on the left: Is racism the primary problem in America today, or the outgrowth of a system that oppresses all poor people?
docs.lead_paragraph: Adolph Reed is a son of the segregated South, a native of New Orleans who organized poor Black people and antiwar soldiers in the late 1960s and became a leading Socialist scholar at a trio of top universities.

headline.main: A Black Marxist Scholar Wanted to Talk About Race. It Ignited a Fury.
headline.print_headline: A Marxist’s Views on Race and Class Expose Rift Among Socialists

docs.abstract: Carlos Delgado remembered the difficulty of demonstrating alone 16 years ago. Now, he and current players are encouraged by a growing sense of solidarity with Black athletes.
docs.snippet: Carlos Delgado remembered the difficulty of demonstrating alone 16 years ago. Now, he and current players are encouraged by a growing sense of solidarity with Black athletes.
docs.lead_paragraph: Carlos Delgado, the former Toronto Blue Jays and Mets slugger, was playing basketball with his 13-year-old son at their home in Puerto Rico on Wednesday evening when he noticed a news alert on his phone: The Milwaukee Bucks players were sitting out of their N.B.A. playoff game to protest systemic racism and police brutality following the shooting of Jacob Blake, a Black man, by police in Kenosha, Wis.

headline.main: After a Long Lull, Protesting Is Taking Hold Across Baseball
headline.print_headline: After a Long Lull, Protesting Becomes Popular Again in Baseball

docs.abstract: His family often asks me about Black Lives Matter and racism. My boyfriend is annoyed, but I’m happy to teach them.
docs.snippet: His family often asks me about Black Lives Matter and racism. My boyfriend is annoyed, but I’m happy to teach them.
docs.lead_paragraph: I am a young Black woman who’s been quarantining with my white boyfriend for months. It’s been mostly great for us as a couple. When we visit his family nearby, they often ask me about the Black Lives Matter protests, in which we’re participating. I find them genuinely interested, respectful and curious about why expressions like “All Lives Matter” are racist. I’m happy to engage. But my boyfriend gets furious with them! He turns simple questions into big fights. What am I missing?

headline.main: My Boyfriend Is Mad At His White Parents for Me. But I Don’t Care.

docs.abstract: Individuals like Jackie Robinson, Muhammad Ali and Colin Kaepernick changed society. Can this generation do it by banding together?
docs.snippet: Individuals like Jackie Robinson, Muhammad Ali and Colin Kaepernick changed society. Can this generation do it by banding together?
docs.lead_paragraph: In June, as the National Basketball Association prepared to restart its season amid the twin crises of the pandemic and the nationwide protests against racial injustice, the general manager of one team told the sportswriter Sam Amick, “You know and I know why we are playing — for the money.”

headline.main: Athletes Are Finished Playing America’s Rigged Game
headline.print_headline: The N.B.A. Finds Social Justice Is a Team Sport

docs.abstract: A four-day showing of apocalypse now.
docs.snippet: A four-day showing of apocalypse now.
docs.lead_paragraph: I’ve been thinking about the two families we’ve encountered over the past two weeks. The Biden family is emotionally open, rendered vulnerable by tragedy and driven by a powerful desire to connect. The Trump family is emotionally closed, isolated by enmity and driven by a powerful desire to dominate.

headline.main: Trump and the Politics of ‘Mean World’
headline.print_headline: Trump and the Politics of ‘Mean World’

docs.abstract: For community activists on the South Side of Chicago, words are insufficient, and an embrace of the Black Lives Matter movement requires caring for communities that both Democrats and Republicans have ignored.
docs.snippet: For community activists on the South Side of Chicago, words are insufficient, and an embrace of the Black Lives Matter movement requires caring for communities that both Democrats and Republicans have ignored.
docs.lead_paragraph: CHICAGO — The old guard of this city’s Roseland neighborhood, a community on the South Side famous for molding a young Barack Obama and infamous for its current blight, has never forgotten the fruit trees.

headline.main: Are Racial Attitudes Really Changing? Some Black Activists Are Skeptical
headline.print_headline: In a Black Chicago Community, Doubt Defies Hope for Change
